	<h2>Understanding Privacy Needs in Stockton Neighborhoods</h2>

	<h3>Common Privacy Challenges</h3>
	<p>Stockton homeowners face unique privacy obstacles:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Close lot lines:</strong> Many neighborhoods have homes 10-15 feet apart</li>
		<li><strong>Two-story neighbors:</strong> Standard 6-foot fences don't block upper floor views</li>
		<li><strong>Pool regulations:</strong> Safety codes require specific fence designs around pools</li>
		<li><strong>HOA restrictions:</strong> Many communities limit fence height, materials, and colors</li>
		<li><strong>Street-facing yards:</strong> Front yard privacy limited to 3-4 feet in most areas</li>
		<li><strong>Alley access:</strong> Rear alleys common, requiring durable privacy solutions</li>
		<li><strong>Climate considerations:</strong> Central Valley heat affects material performance</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>What Makes a Privacy Fence Effective</h3>
	<p>True privacy fencing needs these characteristics:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Adequate height:</strong> Minimum 6 feet for ground-level privacy, 8 feet for two-story homes</li>
		<li><strong>Minimal gaps:</strong> Board spacing under 1/2 inch prevents sight lines</li>
		<li><strong>Solid construction:</strong> No warping, twisting, or shrinkage creating gaps</li>
		<li><strong>Strategic placement:</strong> Positioned to block specific sight lines, not just property boundaries</li>
		<li><strong>Visual density:</strong> Materials that don't become transparent when backlit</li>
		<li><strong>Sound dampening:</strong> Mass and density help reduce noise transmission</li>
	</ul>

